some cases, the government uses fiscal policy,

10
00:00:47,640 --> 00:00:53,090
let's say, with the intent of giving the economy
a boost -- and the policy has the unintended

11
00:00:53,090 --> 00:00:58,149
consequence of reducing spending by the other
sectors, like household consumption and/or

12
00:00:58,149 --> 00:01:02,760
business investment. This “crowding out”
of the household and business spending can

13
00:01:02,760 --> 00:01:07,860
be direct, like building a library and having
household purchases of books decline, or like

14
00:01:07,860 --> 00:01:11,970
providing government dollars for charter schools,
and seeing households spend less on private

15
00:01:11,970 --> 00:01:18,370
tuition at Catholic schools; or the crowding
out can be the indirect result of the expansionary

16
00:01:18,370 --> 00:01:24,460
policy. If the government increases spending
and/or decreases taxes it will increase its

17
00:01:24,460 --> 00:01:29,899
own deficit. Then the government needs to
borrow in order to pay for the overspending.

18
00:01:29,900 --> 00:01:35,080
This added demand pressure for credit drives
up the price of credit, or interest rates.

19
00:01:35,080 --> 00:01:39,890
As interest rates rise, consumption and investment
spending fall. The amount of crowding out

20
00:01:39,890 --> 00:01:44,140
